# SECTION 1: THE TWO TASK-FLOW BUGS

### Bug 1: Why the Leader Fails to Auto-Resume when Teammates Finish
When a background teammate or subagent finishes, `handle_task_completed` is called, which invokes `maybe_resume_after_background` [2]. However, look at the first guard check in that function [2]:
```rust
pub(crate) async fn maybe_resume_after_background(app: &mut App, tx: &EventSender) {
    let all_bg_done = app
        .background_tasks
        .values()
        .all(|bt| bt.status.is_terminal());
    if !all_bg_done {
        return;
    }
    if app.turn_started_at.is_some() // <--- THE COLD SHUNT!
        && app.pending_tool_calls.is_empty()
        && ...
```

#### The Bug
When a subagent or teammate is spawned in the background (which is the standard case for long-running tasks), **the leader's spawning turn finishes immediately [1, 2].** It returns a successful "Spawned" tool result [2], completes the turn, and clears **`app.turn_started_at = None`** [1, 2]. 

Because `app.turn_started_at` is `None` [1, 2], when your background agents finally finish (minutes later) and call `maybe_resume_after_background` [2], **the guard check exits immediately!** 

#### The Impact
The leader remains completely dead and parked. It has no idea it needs to wake up and digest the teammate's results. You are forced to type a manual nudge or dummy message to start a new user turn, which finally forces the leader to read the completed task status [1, 2].

